1
00:00:00,100 --> 00:00:03,962
CodeRabbit scanned 470 GitHub repos.

2
00:00:03,912 --> 00:00:08,787
AI-generated code creates 1.7 times more bugs than human code.

3
00:00:08,787 --> 00:00:15,425
75 percent of those are logic errors — where the code looks right, passes review, and breaks in production.

4
00:00:15,425 --> 00:00:17,612
The agent says done.

5
00:00:17,612 --> 00:00:19,550
The code is wrong.

6
00:00:19,550 --> 00:00:21,537
Nobody checked.

7
00:00:21,537 --> 00:00:23,575
Jake's Daily Build.

8
00:00:23,575 --> 00:00:25,325
What we built.

9
00:00:25,325 --> 00:00:26,975
What broke.

10
00:00:26,975 --> 00:00:28,825
What I learned.

11
00:00:28,825 --> 00:00:31,375
This is Trust But Verify.

12
00:00:31,375 --> 00:00:34,587
AI coding agents grade their own homework.

13
00:00:34,587 --> 00:00:39,162
They finish a task, report "all criteria met," and you move on.

14
00:00:39,162 --> 00:00:46,087
But Anthropic's research separates the transcript — what the agent says happened — from the outcome — what actually changed.

15
00:00:46,087 --> 00:00:51,612
A flight-booking agent says "your flight is booked" while no reservation exists in the database.

16
00:00:51,612 --> 00:00:53,812
The words are confident.

17
00:00:53,812 --> 00:00:56,075
The reality is empty.

18
00:00:56,075 --> 00:00:58,850
March 17th, our system.

19
00:00:58,850 --> 00:01:01,750
One session, twelve features built.

20
00:01:01,750 --> 00:01:04,962
The agent reported success on every one.

21
00:01:04,962 --> 00:01:07,387
Next day — nothing committed.

22
00:01:07,387 --> 00:01:09,700
Twelve features, gone.

23
00:01:09,700 --> 00:01:11,437
Not failed.

24
00:01:11,437 --> 00:01:13,425
Just never saved.

25
00:01:13,425 --> 00:01:17,787
The agent did the work, reported it, and skipped the last step.

26
00:01:17,787 --> 00:01:22,187
Stack Overflow put it this way: "Eventually the agent forgets.

27
00:01:22,187 --> 00:01:26,737
It starts forgetting more and more until you have to stop it and start over.

28
00:01:26,737 --> 00:01:29,550
Mistakes compound over runtime.

29
00:01:29,550 --> 00:01:32,575
By the end, they're baked into the code.

30
00:01:32,575 --> 00:01:35,025
So we built a babysitter.

31
00:01:35,025 --> 00:01:37,775
230 lines of bash.

32
00:01:37,775 --> 00:01:43,075
It runs after every sub-agent completes a task, checking the things agents lie about.

33
00:01:43,075 --> 00:01:46,312
Git status — is the working directory clean?

34
00:01:46,312 --> 00:01:49,587
Uncommitted files means unfinished work.

35
00:01:49,587 --> 00:01:53,162
That catches the March 17th problem instantly.

36
00:01:53,162 --> 00:01:57,525
Recent commits — did anything get committed in the last 30 minutes?

37
00:01:57,525 --> 00:01:59,875
No commit, no work.

38
00:01:59,875 --> 00:02:01,387
Simple.

39
00:02:01,387 --> 00:02:06,862
Push status — committed but not pushed means the work exists locally but isn't backed up.

40
00:02:06,862 --> 00:02:09,550
One disk failure and it's gone.

41
00:02:09,550 --> 00:02:13,375
File existence — task was "create a deploy script.

42
00:02:13,375 --> 00:02:16,050
Does deploy.sh exist?

43
00:02:16,050 --> 00:02:20,550
Agents report building files that don't exist more often than you'd think.

44
00:02:20,550 --> 00:02:25,387
The design decision that matters most: none of these checks use an LLM.

45
00:02:25,387 --> 00:02:28,125
It's bash, git, and grep.

46
00:02:28,125 --> 00:02:30,825
Deterministic verification.

47
00:02:30,825 --> 00:02:39,225
Microsoft's Agent Governance Toolkit makes the same argument — using an LLM to judge whether an LLM did good work is a recursive trust problem.

48
00:02:39,225 --> 00:02:43,075
Your safety layer can hallucinate just like your worker.

49
00:02:43,075 --> 00:02:45,037
So don't use one.

50
00:02:45,037 --> 00:02:51,525
Results feed into a scorecard tracking success rate, steering interventions, and token usage over time.

51
00:02:51,525 --> 00:02:53,537
Patterns emerge.

52
00:02:53,537 --> 00:02:57,800
When agents consistently forget to push, that becomes a rule.

53
00:02:57,800 --> 00:03:00,825
The rule gets enforced in the next prompt.

54
00:03:00,825 --> 00:03:04,275
The system improves through its own failure data.

55
00:03:04,275 --> 00:03:08,162
First batch after building this: four out of four passed.

56
00:03:08,162 --> 00:03:10,325
Zero steering needed.

57
00:03:10,325 --> 00:03:13,012
Average three minutes per task.

58
00:03:13,012 --> 00:03:18,587
Not because the agents were perfect — because the babysitter catches gaps before we call it done.

59
00:03:18,587 --> 00:03:21,037
But here's where we fall short.

60
00:03:21,037 --> 00:03:23,937
We researched four approaches this week.

61
00:03:23,937 --> 00:03:30,075
Anthropic's full eval framework — transcripts, environment verification, LLM judges.

62
00:03:30,075 --> 00:03:32,062
Enterprise-grade.

63
00:03:32,062 --> 00:03:38,400
The Superpowers methodology does two-stage review: spec compliance first, code quality second.

64
00:03:38,400 --> 00:03:42,887
TDD Guard physically blocks file writes unless there's a failing test.

65
00:03:42,887 --> 00:03:48,425
The author found hooks that prevent bad behavior beat instructions that request good behavior.

66
00:03:48,425 --> 00:03:52,387
GitHub Agentic Workflows run CI on agent output.

67
00:03:52,387 --> 00:03:54,537
Most teams do nothing.

68
00:03:54,537 --> 00:03:56,587
Fire and forget.

69
00:03:56,787 --> 00:03:58,699
We're in between.

70
00:03:58,649 --> 00:04:02,199
Our babysitter checks structure, not semantics.

71
00:04:02,199 --> 00:04:04,574
It knows files exist.

72
00:04:04,574 --> 00:04:07,374
It doesn't know if the code is correct.

73
00:04:07,374 --> 00:04:10,137
It verifies the agent committed.

74
00:04:10,137 --> 00:04:13,099
Not that the commit does what was asked.

75
00:04:13,099 --> 00:04:16,124
That's the gap — structure versus meaning.

76
00:04:16,124 --> 00:04:20,724
Checking that a student turned in an essay, not whether it answers the prompt.

77
00:04:20,724 --> 00:04:22,699
Two things to build.

78
00:04:22,699 --> 00:04:26,499
One: a TDD flag for babysit.sh.

79
00:04:26,499 --> 00:04:30,737
When enabled, scan changed source files for matching test files.

80
00:04:30,737 --> 00:04:34,612
Touched auth.js with no auth.test.js?

81
00:04:34,612 --> 00:04:36,099
Warning.

82
00:04:36,099 --> 00:04:40,549
Not a blocker — we're vibe coders, not a Java shop — but a signal.

83
00:04:40,549 --> 00:04:45,112
Start as a warning, graduate to hard failure on critical paths.

84
00:04:45,112 --> 00:04:48,174
Two: a semantic compliance layer.

85
00:04:48,174 --> 00:04:56,699
After deterministic checks pass, a lightweight LLM evaluates: given the task description and the git diff, did the agent do what was asked?

86
00:04:56,699 --> 00:04:59,562
The bash layer stays as foundation.

87
00:04:59,562 --> 00:05:03,187
The LLM layer is additive, not replacement.

88
00:05:03,187 --> 00:05:05,124
Trust the bash.

89
00:05:05,124 --> 00:05:07,362
Augment with judgment.

90
00:05:07,362 --> 00:05:10,162
Deterministic catches forgetting.

91
00:05:10,162 --> 00:05:13,124
Semantic catches misunderstanding.

92
00:05:13,124 --> 00:05:16,187
Together, both failure modes covered.

93
00:05:16,187 --> 00:05:18,624
That's Trust But Verify.

94
00:05:18,624 --> 00:05:20,274
I'm Jake.

95
00:05:20,274 --> 00:05:22,649
Catch you next episode.

